# Code Quality Rules

## File Size Limits
| File Type | Target | Hard Limit | Action at Limit |
|-----------|--------|------------|-----------------|
| Page component (page.tsx) | <300 lines | 400 lines | Extract into sub-components |
| React component | <250 lines | 350 lines | Split by responsibility |
| API route file | <400 lines | 500 lines | Split into sub-routers |
| Pipeline module | <300 lines | 400 lines | Extract focused helpers |
| Test file | <500 lines | No limit | Split by feature area |

## Before Writing Any Code
1. Check for existing patterns in the codebase that solve the same problem
2. Check if a utility/helper already exists in `pipeline/utils.py` or `frontend/lib/utils.ts`
3. Check `pipeline/db/schema.py` for existing tables that might cover the need
4. NEVER duplicate logic — extract shared code into a common module

## Module Organization
- One concern per file. If a file does two unrelated things, split it.
- Import from barrels (`pipeline/db/__init__.py`, `frontend/lib/api.ts`, `frontend/types/api.ts`)
- Keep the dependency graph acyclic — pipeline modules should NOT import from api/routes

## Error Handling (Every Module)
- Validate inputs at boundaries (route handlers, import parsers)
- Handle errors explicitly — no silent failures
- Log at appropriate levels: `info` for success, `warning` for recoverable, `error` for failures
- Never expose stack traces or internal details to the API consumer

## Performance Awareness
- Avoid N+1 queries — use eager loading or batch queries
- Don't load entire tables into memory — use pagination and limits
- Batch AI categorization calls (already done in `categorizer.py`)
- Cache expensive computations (market data, tax calculations) with appropriate TTLs

## Tech Debt Prevention
- If you touch a file with known tech debt (see ARCHITECTURE.md), fix or reduce it
- Every new feature must follow existing patterns — don't introduce new patterns without justification
- Prefer the smallest change that achieves the goal
- Leave the codebase better than you found it
